Project Goal: 
Develop a robust, testable, and maintainable Telegram bot for identifying and executing cryptocurrency arbitrage opportunities using native Rust exchange clients, deployed on Cloudflare Workers with KV storage, all the detail under /docs folder


Core Principles:

Test-Driven Development (TDD) is Law:
Write tests before writing implementation code for any new feature or bug fix.
All tests must pass before any code is considered complete or merged.
Utilize cargo test for all unit, integration, and (where feasible) end-to-end tests.
Comprehensive Test Coverage is Mandatory:
Aim for high test coverage (e.g., >90%) across all critical modules, especially arbitrage logic, exchange interactions, and Cloudflare service integrations.
Regularly review coverage reports using cargo-tarpaulin and address gaps.
Linting & Formatting Perfection:
Code must pass all linting rules (cargo clippy with strict configuration) and be formatted (cargo fmt) before commit.
Automate this with pre-commit hooks if possible.
Always Use Latest Stable & Secure Versions:
Technology: Default to the latest stable versions of Rust, cargo, wrangler, and other dependencies.
Security: Regularly update dependencies using cargo audit to patch vulnerabilities.
Cloudflare-Native First:
Deployment: The primary deployment target is Cloudflare Workers. Design and optimize for this environment using WASM compilation.
KV for Data Storage: Leverage KV for storing structured data like trade history, user configurations, and persistent opportunity records.
Secrets: All API keys (Telegram, exchange APIs) and sensitive credentials must be stored securely using Cloudflare Workers secrets.

Modular & Service-Oriented Design:
Telegram Interface: Isolate Telegram bot command handling and message parsing.
Exchange Service: Abstract all exchange API interactions into a dedicated service layer. This layer handles HTTP calls, error normalization, and rate limiting logic.
Arbitrage Engine: The core arbitrage detection logic should be a distinct module, configurable and testable in isolation.
Cloudflare Services Clients: Create specific clients or wrappers for interacting with KV to centralize logic and facilitate mocking.
Robust Error Handling & Logging:
Implement comprehensive error handling throughout the application using Rust's Result type.
Use structured logging. For Workers, this might involve console_log! initially, but consider patterns for capturing critical errors.
Gracefully handle exchange API errors, network issues, and unexpected responses.
Efficient Resource Usage (Worker Constraints):
Be mindful of Worker CPU time, memory usage, and execution limits.
Optimize algorithms and data handling for performance within these constraints using Rust's zero-cost abstractions.
Minimize cold start impact where possible.
Rust for Memory Safety and Performance:
Develop the entire bot using Rust to ensure memory safety, performance, and catch errors at compile time.
Use strict type checking with Rust's type system.
Documentation in /docs & In-Code:
/docs Directory: Maintain detailed documentation for:
Core arbitrage strategies and logic.
Setup and configuration (including environment variables).
Deployment procedures using Wrangler.
API interactions (Telegram commands, exchange API specifics).
Data models for KV storage.
In-Code: Use Rust doc comments (///) for all functions, structs, and complex logic sections. Comments should explain why, not just what.
Cargo for Package Management:
Strictly use cargo for all dependency management to ensure efficient and deterministic builds.
Configuration Management:
Use environment variables (managed via Wrangler .toml files and secrets) for configuration that changes between environments (dev, staging, prod) or contains sensitive data.
Consider KV for dynamic runtime configuration if needed.

Workflow Adherence:

Git Workflow: Use feature branches, clear commit messages, and (if applicable) pull requests for code review before merging to the main branch.
CI/CD (Future Consideration): Plan for eventually integrating a CI/CD pipeline (e.g., GitHub Actions) to automate testing, linting, and deployment on pushes/merges to the main branch.